What the evaluator will see — end to end:
Customer submits claim (React UI)
        ↓
claims-module  →  saves to Postgres (claims schema)
               →  publishes ClaimSubmittedEvent  →  Kafka topic: claim-events
                                                          ↓
                                              notification-module (Kafka consumer)
                                                  → sends email (Mailhog)
                                                  → writes to notification_log
                                                          ↓
                                              reporting-module (Kafka consumer)
                                                  → updates KPI snapshot
                                                          ↓
                                              audit-module (Kafka consumer)
                                                  → appends to audit_log (immutable)
This is genuine event-driven architecture:

Real Kafka broker (Redpanda in Docker)
Real topics (claim-events, audit-events, payment-events)
Real producer/consumer separation (publisher doesn't know who consumes)
Real fan-out (one event → multiple consumers)
Real async (claim submission returns immediately; notification happens after)
Redpanda Console UI showing messages flowing through topics in real time
The evaluator can open the Redpanda Console at localhost:8082, submit a claim, and watch the event appear in the topic. That's more convincing than most microservices POCs.